    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and kept seeing stuff about lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles and how the body gets rid of it after a set? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! When you do a high-intensity interval training (HIIT) workout, your muscles are like a bustling city of hardworking citizens, and lactic acid is like the waste they produce. During intense exercise, your muscles need more energy than oxygen can provide, so they switch to a process called anaerobic respiration. This process produces lactic acid as a byproduct, much like a factory producing waste while trying to keep up with demand.\n\nNow, when the workout is over, your body is like a diligent cleanup crew. It starts to clear out the lactic acid, converting it back into pyruvate, which can then be used for energy again. This process is called the Cori cycle, and it's like a recycling program for your muscles. The lactic acid is transported to the liver, where it's converted back into glucose, which can then be used as fuel for future workouts. So, in a way, your body is like a clever little city that knows how to manage its waste and keep everything running smoothly.",
      "source": "target",
